{% if use_cqrs %}
## CQRS via Symfony Messenger

Commands and Queries are plain PHP objects (no interface required by default, but `CommandInterface` and `QueryInterface` marker interfaces are recommended).

```
Application/
├── Command/
│   └── CreateUser/
│       ├── CreateUserCommand.php      # readonly class CreateUserCommand
│       └── CreateUserCommandHandler.php
├── Query/
│   └── GetUser/
│       ├── GetUserQuery.php           # readonly class GetUserQuery
│       └── GetUserQueryHandler.php
```

### Command Bus

Commands represent intent to change state. A command handler:

- Is registered automatically via `#[AsMessageHandler]`
- Performs one unit of work
- Wraps the operation in a database transaction
- Returns `void` or a generated ID

```php
#[AsMessageHandler]
final class CreateUserCommandHandler
{
    public function __construct(
        private readonly UserRepositoryInterface $users,
        private readonly PasswordHasherInterface $hasher,
    ) {}

    public function __invoke(CreateUserCommand $command): void
    {
        // validate, build aggregate, persist
    }
}
```

### Query Bus

Queries return read models. A query handler never modifies state:

```php
#[AsMessageHandler]
final class GetUserQueryHandler
{
    public function __invoke(GetUserQuery $query): UserReadModel
    {
        // fetch and return a DTO/read model
    }
}
```

### Messenger Configuration

```yaml
# config/packages/messenger.yaml
framework:
    messenger:
        buses:
            command.bus:
                middleware:
                    - doctrine_transaction
            query.bus: ~
```

Dispatch from a controller:

```php
$this->commandBus->dispatch(new CreateUserCommand(...));
$user = $this->queryBus->dispatch(new GetUserQuery($id));
```

{% endif %}

